# World Cup 2026 Betting App

## Your role
You are a senior software engineer. Keep solutions simple, pragmatic, and well-explained. Prefer the smallest change that solves the problem. Reuse existing patterns before introducing new ones.

---

## What this app is (product intent — do not change without owner approval)
A private, invite-only score-prediction game for FIFA World Cup 2026 (Jun 11 – Jul 19, 2026). Approved users predict match scores and tournament outcomes and compete on a live leaderboard. The admin approves registrations and recalculates scores. The app is shared with a small group of friends — **not a public product**.

It must be:
- Free to host (Vercel + Supabase free tiers — no paid Node host).
- Installable as a PWA on iOS and Android.
- Bilingual (English + Hebrew with full RTL).
- Strict on rate limits — TheSportsDB free tier is 30 req/min. The serverless `/api/football/*` layer caches for 60 s and uses single-flight de-dupe to stay well under that.

---

## Stack — Vercel + Supabase only
- **Frontend:** React 19 + Vite 7 + Mantine v8, deployed to **Vercel**.
- **Database:** **Supabase** (Postgres). Tables: `users`, `predictions`.
- **Backend logic:** Vercel **Serverless Functions** under `/api/*`. Do **not** use Railway or any other Node host — keep hosting to Vercel + Supabase only, free of charge.
- **External APIs:** TheSportsDB v1 (free key `123` by default, kept server-side; FIFA World Cup is league `4429`, season `2026`), Resend (email, optional).
- Secrets live in Vercel env vars. The browser only sees `VITE_*` public vars.
- Passwords hashed with **bcryptjs** (pure JS — `bcrypt` native binary breaks on Vercel).
- Auth is **JWT** (7-day expiry), signed server-side, attached by `serverApi` axios interceptor.

## Mobile / PWA
This is a **React web app, not React Native**. It must be installable as a **PWA** so users can "Add to Home Screen" on iOS and Android. Required: web manifest, `vite-plugin-pwa` service worker, iOS `apple-touch-icon` + `apple-mobile-web-app-*` meta tags, and 192/512 px maskable icons.

## Hebrew language support (i18n)
The app must support Hebrew. Use a single i18n layer (`react-i18next`) with `en` and `he` translations. Set `<html dir="rtl" lang="he">` when locale is Hebrew. All user-facing strings come from translation keys — never hard-code text in components.

## Data fetching strategy
Football fixtures only change between stages, not during them. Therefore:
- **One API call per stage** (Group Stage, R32, R16, QF, SF, Third Place, Final). Cache the result client-side (`useMatches`) until the stage advances.
- **Never refetch the full schedule on route change.**
- TheSportsDB free V1 does **not** provide in-play / live status — events flip directly from `SCHEDULED` to `FINISHED`. The `useTodayMatches` hook therefore polls slowly (every 5 minutes) and on tab-visibility changes; there is no fast in-play polling. Live in-play scores would require a paid upgrade to TheSportsDB V2 ($9/mo).
- The serverless `/api/football/*` proxy adds a 60 s in-memory cache + single-flight to absorb bursts. It also caches the per-team metadata (badges, short names) for the lifetime of the serverless instance.

## Profile page (`/profile`) — required content
1. **Account details:** name, email, joined date.
2. **Bet Summary:**
   - 🏆 Tournament Winner
   - ⚽ Top Scorer
   - 🎯 Top Assist
   - 📝 Match Predictions — number of matches the user has placed a prediction on.
3. **📋 My Match Predictions** — list every match the user predicted, formatted as `Mexico vs South Africa  0–0`. Sort by match kickoff date.
4. **🎯 Tournament Bets** — editable **only before** the tournament starts (Jun 11, 2026). After kickoff, render as locked / read-only.
   - 🏅 **World Cup Winner** — dropdown of all national teams playing in the World Cup (live football API).
   - ⚽ **Top Scorer** — dropdown from a fixed list (`TOP_SCORERS_LIST`, supplied by user; leave placeholder until then).
   - 🎯 **Top Assist** — dropdown from a fixed list (`TOP_ASSISTS_LIST`, supplied by user; leave placeholder until then).

## General principles
- Keep it simple — avoid premature abstraction and extra dependencies.
- Reuse existing patterns: `AuthContext`, `serverApi`, the `useMatches` / `useTodayMatches` hooks, CSS modules.
- Never expose service-role keys or third-party API tokens to the browser.
- Validate inputs both client-side and server-side.
- When in doubt, ask the user before introducing a new library or architectural change.

